TY  - JOUR
AB  - Historical accounts suggest that Jewish &#xe9;migr&#xe9;s from Nazi Germany revolutionized US science. To analyze the &#xe9;migr&#xe9;s' effects on chemical innovation in the United States, we compare changes in patenting by US inventors in research fields of &#xe9;migr&#xe9;s with fields of other German chemists. Patenting by US inventors increased by 31 percent in &#xe9;migr&#xe9; fields. Regressions which instrument for &#xe9;migr&#xe9; fields with pre-1933 fields of dismissed German chemists confirm a substantial increase in US invention. Inventor-level data indicate that &#xe9;migr&#xe9;s encouraged innovation by attracting new researchers to their fields, rather than by increasing the productivity of incumbent inventors.
